# ssim2_strip_vs_whole_2026-05-22.csv — metadata

date: 2026-05-22
repo: imazen/zenmetrics
crate: ssim2-gpu
git_commit: (current @ — see jj log)
host: water-cooled AMD Ryzen 9 7950X, 128 GB RAM
gpu: NVIDIA driver 596.21, CUDA 13.2 (cubecl-cuda dynamic load)
backend: CudaRuntime (CUDA)
build: cargo build --release -p ssim2-gpu --example bench_strip_vs_whole \
                  --no-default-features --features cubecl-types,cuda
run:   ./target/release/examples/bench_strip_vs_whole

note: bench_strip_vs_whole.rs runs sequentially per (size, mode) with
      n_warmup=3, n_measure=8. Times reported in milliseconds via
      `Instant::now()` bracketing `client.sync()` to force device-host
      sync, eliminating async-submit timing artefacts.

note: working_set_mb is a static-estimate function of (strip_alloc_h,
      image_w) — NOT measured directly via nvidia-smi. The estimate
      matches `memory_mode::estimate_strip_gpu_memory_bytes` /
      `estimate_gpu_memory_bytes` modulo packing overhead. Use
      `nvidia-smi --query-gpu=memory.used` mid-benchmark for a
      runtime check.

note: 24 MP whole-image is SKIP_OOM because the full ~7.5 GB
      allocation exceeds the conservative 8 GB headroom budget when
      ssim2 is the only metric live. The strip path completes at
      24 MP because its working set is bounded by the strip
      dimensions rather than the image dimensions.

per-mp summary (strip path):
  1.05 MP:  7.7 ms,  491 MB
  4.19 MP: 19.8 ms,  981 MB
 12.00 MP: 52.1 ms, 1916 MB
 24.00 MP:100.9 ms, 2875 MB

whole vs strip wall-time ratio:
  1.05 MP: 1.1× (strip faster — fewer reductions to launch)
  4.19 MP: 0.6× (strip slower — halo recompute overhead)
 12.00 MP: 0.6× (strip slower — same reason)
 24.00 MP: ∞   (whole skip-OOM)

interpretation: strip mode trades wall time (~1.7× slower at 12 MP)
for memory (~2.6× less working set at 12 MP, makes 24 MP possible at
all). For sweep workers running multiple metrics concurrently this is
the right trade — 24 MP becomes feasible on 8/12 GB consumer GPUs.
